round-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Matthews|Daniel Matthews]]\n| style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Erik Knudsen]]\n| {{NA|Mentioned only}}\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| Erik Knudsen{{ref|cameo|C}}\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Xavier Chavez|Xavier Chavez]]\n| style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Franky G]]\n| Franky G{{ref|special|S}}\n| style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| Franky G{{ref|cameo|C}}\n| style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| {{NA|Mentioned only{{ref|special|S}}}}\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Denlon|Jeff Denlon]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Angus Macfadyen]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Lynn Denlon|Lynn Denlon]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Bahar Soomekh]]\n| style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" | \n| {{NA|Mentioned only}}\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Peter Strahm]]\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Scott Patterson]]\n| {{NA|Mentioned only}}\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Lindsey Perez|Lindsey Perez]]\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Athena Karkanis]]\n| {{NA|Mentioned only}}\n| Athena Karkanis\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Art Blank|Art Blank]]\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Justin Louis]]\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Dan Erickson|Dan Erickson]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Mark Rolston]]\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Mallick|Mallick]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Greg Bryk]]\n| style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| Greg Bryk\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Brit|Brit]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Julie Benz]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Pamela Jenkins|Pamela Jenkins]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | Samantha Lemole\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#William Easton|William Easton]]\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Peter Outerbridge]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Bobby Dagen|Bobby Dagen]]\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Sean Patrick Flanery]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" | \n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Matt Gibson|Matt Gibson]]\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Chad Donella]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" | \n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Logan Nelson|Logan Nelson<br>{{small|Jigsaw}}]]\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Matt Passmore]]\n| style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Detective Halloran|Det. Halloran]]\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Callum Keith Rennie]]\n| style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! [[List of Saw characters#Eleanor Bonneville|Eleanor Bonneville]]\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| Hannah Emily Anderson\n| style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n|-\n! Det. Ezekiel \"Zeke\" Banks\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Chris Rock]]\n|-\n! Marcus Banks\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Samuel L. Jackson]]\n|-\n! Det. William Schenk\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Max Minghella]]\n|-\n! Capt. Angie Garza\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background-color:#D3D3D3;\" |\n| [[Marisol Nichols]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Crew===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:99%;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10%;\"| Crew\n! colspan=9| Film\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| ''[[Saw II]]''\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| ''[[Saw III]]''\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| ''[[Saw IV]]''\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| ''[[Saw V]]''\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| ''[[Saw VI]]''\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral]]''\n|-\n! Cinematographer\n| colspan=\"6\"| David A. Armstrong\n| colspan=\"1\"| Brian Gedge\n| colspan=\"1\"| Ben Nott\n| Jordan Oram\n|-\n! Editor(s)\n| colspan=\"3\"| [[Kevin Greutert]]\n| Kevin Greutert and Brett Sullivan\n| Kevin Greutert\n| colspan=\"2\"| Andrew Coutts\n| Kevin Greutert\n| Dev Singh\n|-\n! Composer\n| colspan=\"9\" | [[Charlie Clouser]]\n|-\n! [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]] rating\n| colspan=\"9\"| R\n|-\n! Running time\n| 102 minutes\n| 92 minutes\n| 108 minutes\n| 92 minutes\n| 92 minutes\n| 90 minutes\n| 90 minutes\n| 92 minutes\n| {{N/A|TBA}}\n|}\n\n==Production==\nFlashbacks from ''[[Saw IV]]'' reveal the roots of the series, presenting John Kramer as a successful [[Civil engineering|civil engineer]] and devoted husband to his wife [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]], who opened a rehab clinic for drug addicts. Jill lost her unborn baby, Gideon, due to the unwitting actions of a drug addict named [[List of Saw characters#Cecil Adams|Cecil]], who fled the scene. ''[[Saw VI]]'' later showed that another drug addict, [[Amanda Young]], also had an unintentional role in the death of Gideon. John grieved over the loss of his child and distanced himself from his friends and his wife.\n\nJohn and Jill eventually drifted apart and divorced. After this turn of events, John found himself trapped by his own complacency until he was diagnosed with inoperable [[cancer]]. Extremely bitter over his squandered life and the loss of his unborn son, John began observing the lives of others and became even more depressed as he saw those around him squandering the gift of life that he had just been denied. John went to a man named William Easton to get money for a cancer treatment, but was denied. Flashbacks from ''[[Saw II]]'' show that, after surviving a [[suicide]] attempt where he drove his car off a cliff, John was \"reborn\", and nurtured the idea that the only way for someone to change is for them to change themselves. Then, in ''[[Saw IV]]'' flashbacks, he designed the first trap and test for Cecil and decided to use the rest of his existence to design more of these \"tests\" or \"games\" as a form of \"instant rehabilitation\" that would change the world, \"one person at a time\". John was soon given the name \"The Jigsaw Killer\" (or \"Jigsaw\"), because he removed a puzzle-piece-shaped chunk of flesh from those who did not escape his traps. John stated that this name was given to him by the media, and that the cut piece of flesh was meant to represent that these victims were each missing something\u2014what he called the \"survival instinct\".\n\nFew of Jigsaw's victims can survive his brutal mechanical traps, which are often [[irony|ironically]] [[symbol]]ic representations of the problems in the victim's life and require them to undergo severe physical and/or psychological [[torture]] to escape.\n\nIn ''[[Saw V]]'', police lieutenant [[Mark Hoffman]]'s ties with John are revealed in a series of flashbacks during the film. Hoffman's sister is murdered by her boyfriend, [[List of Saw characters#Seth Baxter|Seth Baxter]]. Seth is arrested; however, a technicality allowed him to be released, and Hoffman, feeling Seth had not served the full capacity of his sentence, kills him in an inescapable trap designed to look like one of Jigsaw's, laying the blame on him. Jigsaw then kidnaps Hoffman and blackmails him into becoming his apprentice in his \"rehabilitation\" methods, though eventually Hoffman would become a willing apprentice, helping set up John's tests from almost the beginning, starting with [[List of Saw characters#Paul Leahy|Paul]]'s trap.\n\nThe first surviving victim, [[Amanda Young]], views Jigsaw as a hero who ultimately changed her life for the better. Amanda, upon Jigsaw's request, agrees to become his [[Mentorship|prot\u00e9g\u00e9e]]. After Amanda survives, John shows Jill her rehabilitation, and Jill then becomes knowledgeable of John's traps and becomes somewhat of an accomplice as well.\n\nIn ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'', Jigsaw has chained the man who diagnosed his cancer, [[List of Saw characters#Lawrence Gordon|Dr. Lawrence Gordon]], in a dilapidated industrial washroom with [[List of Saw characters#Adam Stanheight|Adam Stanheight]], a photographer who has been tailing the doctor due to belief he is cheating on his wife. Lawrence has instructions to kill Adam by six o'clock, or else his wife and daughter will be killed. Flashbacks show detectives [[David Tapp]] and [[List of Saw characters#Steven Sing|Steven Sing]], who suspect Lawrence of being Jigsaw, following a trail of clues from other Jigsaw traps. Sing's death from a shotgun trap after saving a victim named Jeff causes Tapp to obsess over catching Jigsaw. Later on, he chases [[List of Saw characters#Zep Hindle|Zep Hindle]], who monitors Adam and Lawrence's tests, and gets shot in the chest. Eventually, Lawrence saws off his own foot in order to escape, leaving Adam in the bathroom while Lawrence goes to try to save his family and get help for Adam. It is later seen in ''Saw 3D'' that Lawrence found a steaming hot pipe and cauterized his wound, stopping the bleeding and ultimately surviving the trap. John catches up with Lawrence and makes him his next apprentice, a fact which he hides from his other accomplices. Flashbacks from ''Saw III'' show that Amanda kidnapped Adam and later returned to suffocate him as an act of \"mercy killing\".\n\n[[File:Saw-cast.jpg|thumb|left|Central actors of the series. From top-left to bottom-right: Tobin Bell, Shawnee Smith, Cary Elwes, Costas Mandylor, Danny Glover, and Betsy Russell.|250px]]\n''[[Saw II]]'' begins with the police tracking a severely weakened Jigsaw to his lair. However, another test is in place, as he and Amanda have kidnapped the son of Detective [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Eric Matthews]] and trapped him and a group of seven convicts, previously framed by Eric, in a house that is slowly being filled with [[Sarin|sarin gas]], with Amanda Young among them. He will trade [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Matthews|Daniel Matthews]]' life for Eric's time, conversing with him until the game is concluded. Eric loses his patience and assaults Jigsaw, forcing him to take him to the house, only to discover that the video feed from inside the house had been pre-recorded, the events actually taking place much earlier; Eric's son was locked in a safe in Jigsaw's warehouse, being kept alive with an oxygen tank. Eric is knocked unconscious by a masked figure and wakes up imprisoned in the bathroom from ''Saw'', which is part of the foundation of the house. Amanda reveals herself to Eric as Jigsaw's prot\u00e9g\u00e9e before leaving him to die. In a flashback from ''Saw III'', Eric manages to escape the bathroom by breaking his foot. He confronts and beats Amanda, demanding to know where his son is. Amanda fights him off and leaves him for dead. A flashback from ''Saw IV'' shows Hoffman later dragging Eric to a prison cell, keeping him alive for a future game.\n\nThe events of ''[[Saw III]]'' and ''[[Saw IV]]'' occur concurrently. ''Saw III'' begins with Jigsaw, weakened and near death, confined to a makeshift hospital bed. Amanda has taken over his work, designing traps of her own; however, these traps are inescapable, as Amanda is convinced that Jigsaw's traps have no effect and that people don't change. A [[List of Saw characters#Lynn Denlon|kidnapped doctor]] is forced to keep Jigsaw alive while another test is performed on [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Denlon|Jeff]], a man obsessed with vengeance against the drunk driver who killed his son. Jigsaw, unwilling to allow a murderer to continue his legacy, designs a test for Amanda as well; she ultimately fails, and it results in the deaths of both Jigsaw and Amanda. ''Saw IV'', meanwhile, revolves around tests meant for [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Rigg|Officer Daniel Rigg]], which are overseen by Hoffman. Rigg fails his test, resulting in the death of Eric Matthews. Rigg is left to bleed to death by Hoffman, who later discovers the bodies of Jigsaw and Amanda. When an [[autopsy]] is performed on Jigsaw, a [[Compact Cassette|cassette tape]] coated in wax is found in his [[stomach]]; the tape informs Hoffman that he is wrong to think that it is all over just because Jigsaw is dead, and he should not expect to go untested.\n\nThe events of ''[[Saw V]]'' show one of Hoffman's first solo tests, five people connected by different roles in a disastrous fire that killed several others are put into four interconnected tests of teamwork, killing off one person in each trap. The two remaining test subjects realize at the final trap that each previous trap was meant to be completed by each of the five people doing a small part, rather than killing one person per trap. With this knowledge, the two work together and barely manage to escape. They are found alive by Special Agent Erikson. Meanwhile, Hoffman has set up FBI Agent [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Peter Strahm]] to appear to be Jigsaw's accomplice, while Strahm pursues Hoffman and is eventually killed due to his inability to follow Hoffman's rules, leaving Hoffman free to continue Jigsaw's \"work\".\n\n''[[Saw VI]]'' begins with Hoffman setting up a game as per John's instructions left in a box for Jill during ''Saw V''. This game centers on insurance executive named [[List of Saw characters#William Easton|William Easton]] who oversees a team responsible for rejecting two-thirds of all insurance claims. As William progresses through four tests, he saves as many people as he can and learns the error of his choice to reject so many policies, which inherently \"kill\" the rejected. His last test is revealed to be a test of forgiveness by the family of [[List of Saw characters#Harold Abbott|Harold Abbott]], a man to whom William rejected a policy in the past, whose son ultimately chooses to kill William using [[hydrofluoric acid]]. Meanwhile, Agent Erickson and the-previously-thought-to-be-dead agent [[List of Saw characters#Lindsey Perez|Lindsey Perez]] search for Agent Strahm with the assistance of Hoffman. Upon finding irregularities in previous murder scenes, Perez and Erickson discover Hoffman's identity, but are killed by him before they can go public with his involvement. Hoffman travels back to the site of William's tests in which Jill attacks him to obey John's final request. She leaves Hoffman in a new Reverse Beartrap left behind by John, though does not leave a key for him to free himself. He is able to manipulate the trap and escapes wounded.\n\n''[[Saw 3D]]'' picks up with Jill and Hoffman battling for control of Jigsaw's legacy. As Jill enters protective custody and makes Hoffman's true identity public, Hoffman sets up a new game involving [[skinhead]]s to find a way to Jill. Meanwhile, Bobby Dagen, a fraud who has written a book about escaping a Jigsaw trap he never experienced, is captured and forced to confront people who knew that he lied about being in a trap. Three of Dagen's friends die and his test concludes with him being forced to reenact the trap that he claimed to have survived before. He fails, which results in the death of his wife. Meanwhile, Hoffman has posed as a corpse and killed several officers to infiltrate the police station. He finds and kills Jill using the Reverse Beartrap. Hoffman attempts to leave town but is captured by Lawrence Gordon and his accomplices, then placed in the bathroom from the first film. Jigsaw is revealed to have aided Lawrence after his game and, in return, Lawrence helped him with subsequent traps. Hoffman is then left shackled in the bathroom to die.\n\n''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]'' begins with a new game presumably being conducted 10 years after the events of John Kramer's death in ''Saw III''. Five people are forced to undergo a series of tests in an abandoned barn, led by John. In the first test, one of the subjects is seemingly killed by buzzsaws after remaining unconscious during instruction. Most of the remaining subjects are killed throughout the game, until only two, Anna and the heavily wounded Ryan, are left. The two of them are drugged and wake up chained on opposite sides of a room. John is revealed to be in the room with them, and he provides them with a shotgun, explaining it is the \"key to their freedom\", before leaving them to escape. Anna attempts to kill Ryan with the shotgun, but the weapon was rigged to backfire, killing her and leaving Ryan to die. Meanwhile, police forces led by Detective Halloran and aided by medical forensic scientists Logan Nelson and Eleanor Bonneville attempt to discover the location and participants in the game, while also struggling to understand how the deceased John could be behind it all. Logan and Eleanor find the location of the game at an abandoned barn owned by Jill Tuck, with Halloran pursuing them, believing they are behind the most recent games. Eleanor is shown escaping, and Logan and Halloran are placed in a room with collars lined with laser cutters around their neck. They are told by John that they must confess their sins to survive. Logan is presumably killed after admitting his error delayed John's diagnosis. Halloran then confesses he let various guilty convicts walk free, deactivating his collar. However, Logan rises from the ground, revealing his collar was harmless. He explains that the game in the barn was the very first game that took place ten years earlier, and that the bodies found by the team were criminals that Halloran let walk free, who Logan placed into an identical game of his own. He reveals he was the participant in the first game who was presumably killed by the buzzsaws, but that John did not believe Logan should die simply because his \"crime\" was merely an accident, and rescued him as a result. John took Logan under his wing, and Logan aided John in all the various traps throughout the series, making him John's very first apprentice. Logan reactivates Halloran's collar, slicing his head open, before slamming the door shut.\n\n===Recurring elements===\n'''Billy'''\n{{Main|Billy the Puppet}}\nBilly is a puppet resembling a [[Ventriloquism#Ventriloquist.27s dummy|ventriloquist's dummy]], sometimes seen riding a [[tricycle]], that has appeared throughout the films and has become a type of [[mascot]] for the series. It is used by the [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw Killer]] to communicate with his victims by delivering televised messages or occasionally in person to describe details of the sadistic traps and the means by which the victims could survive. Viewers have sometimes incorrectly identified the puppet itself as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw]], because of its presence and connection to the killer.\n\nAge and use of the puppet over the course of the films necessitated its reconstruction. According to [[James Wan|Wan]], the original puppet's face for ''Saw'' involved clay, [[papier-m\u00e2ch\u00e9]], and black ping-pong balls with the irises painted in for the eyes, but in later films more sophisticated construction included [[Water jet cutter|waterjet-cut]] foam for the body and remote-controlled [[Audio-Animatronics|animatronics]].<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/saw-2-diary-2|title=Saw 2: Dairy #2|last=Hoffman|first=Gregg|authorlink=Gregg Hoffman|publisher=[[JoBlo.com]]|page=2|date=May 13, 2005|access-date=August 24, 2011<!--|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61AcAwHaK|archive-date=August 24, 2011-->}}</ref>\n\nThe endurance and popularity of the franchise has resulted in the production of ''Billy'' merchandise, as well as references in other media and its use in promotions for the films.\n\n'''\"Hello Zepp\"'''\n{{Main|Hello Zepp}}\n\n\"Hello Zepp\" is a piece of instrumental music that was originally composed by [[Charlie Clouser]] for the first film in the series. In ''Saw'', the implied villain, Zep Hindle, is revealed to actually be a victim of the Jigsaw Killer. (The character's name in the script is spelled \"Zep\", whereas the music titles are spelled \"Zepp\".)<ref>[http://www.imsdb.com/scripts/Saw.html ''Saw'' script] on IMSDb. Accessed 2010-07-23.</ref><ref>[http://saw.ugo.com/?cur=saw-i-soundtrack ''Saw'' track listing] on [[UGO Networks|UGO]]. Accessed 2010-07-23.</ref> As the series continued, the piece was reused in every film as a [[leitmotif]], often being renamed and remixed to accommodate the changing situations and characters. The music was used in every ''Saw'' ending, usually during the revealing of plot revelations and twists which ''Saw'' films often use and it serves as the main theme tune for the whole films.\n\n'''Traps'''<br />\nAn important component of each film is the variety of (usually mechanical in form) traps Jigsaw and his apprentices use on their captives to communicate his message.\n\nAccording to [[David Hackl]], all of the traps are real objects, and not [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]]. They were designed to look horrific but ultimately be safe for the actors in them. Writer [[Marcus Dunstan]] said: \"It's built to function there on the day\", and added: \"It works. So if there's a scalping chair\u2014there really was a chair with working gears to grind and pull your scalp back.\" The most potentially dangerous item was a \"water box\" used in ''[[Saw V]]'', in which one of the actors ([[Scott Patterson]], as [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Peter Strahm]]) had to keep his head submerged as long as possible. Another element of the traps is that [[David Hackl|Hackl]] desired a specific look of rust and menace, but he also wanted them to have a type of beauty about them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/103/1039913p1.html|title=The Anatomy of a Trap: Saw|date=October 29, 2009|access-date=July 22, 2010|last=Monfette|first=Christopher|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61r3t1zc2|archive-date=September 20, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office performance===\n[[File:Saw Guinness award cropped.jpg|thumb|The ''Saw'' series was placed in the [[Guinness World Records]] as the \"Most Successful Horror Franchise\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/07/23/film-saw-idUSN2215375420100723|title=\"Saw\" movie franchise to get Guinness world record|last=Kit|first=Zorianna|work=[[Reuters]]|date=July 22, 2010|access-date=September 21, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61rOhewtb|archive-date=September 21, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Pictured here is director [[Kevin Greutert]] receiving the award at the [[San Diego Comic-Con International|2010 Comic-Con]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/content/printVersion/61775/|title=Splattered: An Interview with James Wan Talking torture, politics and not-so-sweet revenge|last=Foundas|first=Scott|work=[[LA Weekly]]|date=August 30, 2011|access-date=August 19, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/614BzHXY1|archive-date=August 19, 2011| url-status=live}}</ref>]]\n\n''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' grossed $18.2 million its opening weekend and had become [[Lionsgate]]'s second-best opening, after ''[[Fahrenheit 9/11]]''{{'s}} {{nowrap|$23.9 million}} (2004).<ref name=\"BOMOpening\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1540&p=.htm|title='Ray,' 'Saw' See Robust Bows|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=November 1, 2004|access-date=August 17, 2011}}</ref> ''Saw'' went on to gross {{nowrap|$103 million}} worldwide,<ref name=\"SawBOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw.htm|title=Saw (2004)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|access-date=August 16, 2011}}</ref> and is the second-lowest-grossing film in the series after ''[[Saw VI]]''.<ref name=\"Saw.vs\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=sawvs.htm|title='Saw' Vs. 'Saw'|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=August 19, 2011}}</ref> At the time, it became the most profitable horror film after ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (1996). It is the seventh-highest-grossing [[Halloween]] opening weekend.<ref name=\"Halloween opener\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/halloween.htm|title=Halloween Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=September 21, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Saw II]]'' opened at number one with $31.7 million,<ref name=\"BOMWeekend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1930&p=.htm|title='Saw II' Gores 'Zorro' on Halloween Weekend|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|date=October 31, 2005|access-date=August 24, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61AgXubSc|archive-date=August 24, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> and set a Lionsgate Halloween opening weekend record and is also the third-highest-grossing Halloween opener. It became at the time, the widest release in Lionsgate history and one of the best opening weekends for a horror sequel. It is Lionsgate's fourth-highest-grossing film in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"LionsgateBO\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/studio/chart/?studio=lionsgate.htm|title=Lionsgate All Time Box Office Results|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=September 19, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Saw III]]'' placed first by grossing $33.6 million its opening weekend, making it the biggest Halloween debut ever<ref name=\"Halloween opener\"/> and at the time, Lionsgate's highest-opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2191&p=.htm|title='Saw' Sharp in Third Outing|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|date=October 30, 2006|access-date=September 12, 2011}}</ref> It is the highest-grossing film in the series worldwide.<ref name=\"Saw.vs\"/><ref name=\"Saw3BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw3.htm|title=Saw III (2006)|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref> It has the highest-grossing weekend in the series and also Lionsgate's fifth-highest-grossing film in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"Saw.vs\"/><ref name=\"LionsgateBO\"/>\n\n''[[Saw IV]]'' premiered at number one with $32.1 million making it the second-best Halloween weekend opener.<ref name=\"Halloween opener\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2409&p=.htm|title='Saw IV' Loses Little Blood|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=October 29, 2007|access-date=September 21, 2011}}</ref> In ''[[Saw V]]''{{'}}s opening weekend it placed second, being beat by ''[[High School Musical 3: Senior Year]]'', and made $30.1 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2509&p=.htm|title='High School Musical' Cuts Footloose with 'Saw'|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=October 27, 2008|access-date=September 21, 2011}}</ref> It is Lionsgate's tenth-highest-grossing film.<ref name=\"LionsgateBO\"/> ''Saw VI'' opened in second place behind ''[[Paranormal Activity]]'' to $14.1 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2009&wknd=43&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo | publisher=Amazon.com|title=Weekend Box Office Results for October 23\u201325, 2009 | date=October 25, 2009 | access-date=November 24, 2009}}</ref> which is the lowest of all the ''Saw'' films worldwide. It is also the lowest-grossing film in the series.<ref name=\"Saw.vs\"/> ''[[Saw 3D]]'' placed first grossing $22.5 million its opening weekend, with 92% of tickets coming from more than 2,100 3D-equipped locations.<ref name=\"BoxOpeningWeekend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=44&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo | publisher=Amazon.com|title=Weekend Box Office Results for October 29\u201331, 2010 | date=October 31, 2010 | access-date=November 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"VarietyBox\">{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118026633.html|title='Saw 3D' slices competish|last=Stewart|first=Andrew|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|date=October 31, 2010|access-date=November 1, 2010|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5u2DOMCkC|archive-date=November 6, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> It had the fifth-best opening weekend in the ''Saw'' series.<ref name=\"SawOpenings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?view=openings&id=saw.htm&p=.htm|title=Saw Movies Opening Weekends|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 14, 2010}}</ref> It is the most successful film in the franchise since ''Saw IV''.<ref name=\"Saw7BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw7.htm|title=Saw 3D (2010)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|access-date=December 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Saw'' series, when compared to the other high-grossing American horror franchises\u2014''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|A Nightmare on Elm Street]]'', ''[[Child's Play (franchise)|Child's Play]]'', ''[[Friday the 13th (franchise)|Friday the 13th]]'', ''[[Halloween (franchise)|Halloween]]'', the [[Hannibal Lecter]] series, ''[[Psycho (franchise)|Psycho]]'', ''[[Jaws (franchise)|Jaws]]'', ''[[Scream (film series)|Scream]]'', ''[[I Know What You Did Last Summer (franchise)|I Know What You Did Last Summer]]'', ''[[Candyman (1992 film)|Candyman]]'', ''[[Final Destination (franchise)|Final Destination]]'', ''[[The Purge (franchise)|The Purge]]'', ''[[The Omen (film series)|The Omen]]'', ''[[Hellraiser (franchise)|Hellraiser]]'', ''[[Alien (franchise)|Alien]] [[Alien vs. Predator (franchise)|vs.]] [[Predator (franchise)|Predator]]'', ''[[Paranormal Activity (film series)|Paranormal Activity]]'', ''[[The Conjuring]]'', ''[[The Exorcist (film series)|The Exorcist]]'', and ''[[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre (franchise)|The Texas Chainsaw Massacre]]''\u2014with figures adjusted for 2011 inflation,<ref name=\"inflationCalculator\">{{cite web|url=http://www.halfhill.com/inflation.html|title=Tom's Inflation Calculator|publisher=Halfhill.com|format=[[Java Virtual Machine|Java]]|access-date=September 20, 2011}}</ref> is the fifth-highest-grossing horror franchise in the United States and Canada at $457.4 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=saw.htm|title=Saw Movies at the Box Office |work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|access-date=September 17, 2011}}</ref> This list is topped by ''Friday the 13th'' at $687.1 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=fridaythe13th.htm|title=Friday the 13th Movies at the Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=September 21, 2011}}</ref> followed by the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' series with $592.8 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=nightmareonelmstreet.htm|title=A Nightmare on Elm Street at the Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=September 21, 2011}}</ref> with the Hannibal Lecter film series closely behind with $588.7 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=hannibal.htm|title=The Hannibal Lecter at the Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=September 21, 2011}}</ref> Then comes ''Halloween'' with $557.5 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=halloween.htm|title=Halloween at the Box Office |work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=September 21, 2011}}</ref> the ''Scream'' series with $442.9 million and ''The Texas Chainsaw Massacre'' with $304.6 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=texaschainsawmassacre.htm|title=The Texas Chainsaw Massacre at the Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=September 21, 2011}}</ref> and lastly comes the ''Child's Play'' film series with approximately $203 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=childsplay.htm|title=Child's Play at the Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=September 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe box office numbers, unadjusted for inflation are as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=99% border=\"1\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Film\n! rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Release date\n! colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" | Revenue\n! rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Budget\n! rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | References\n|-\n! align=\"center\" | United States<br />Canada\n! align=\"center\" | Other markets\n! align=\"center\" | Worldwide\n|-\n|''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n|{{start date|2004|10|29}}\n|$55,185,045\n|$47,911,300\n|$103,096,345\n|align=\"center\" |$1\u20131.2 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"SawBOM\"/><ref name=\"Collider2011\">{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/james-wan-leigh-whannell-interview-insidious/83806/|title=James Wan & Leigh Whannell Insidious Interview; The Saw Creators Also Discuss Their Untitled Sci-Fi Project, Nihtfall, and Recent Horror Remakes|last=Messer|first=Ron|publisher=Collider.com|date=April 4, 2011|access-date=April 4, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/612ejJ6MJ|archive-date=August 18, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Saw II]]''\n|{{start date|2005|10|28}}\n|$87,039,965\n|$60,708,540\n|$147,748,505\n|align=\"center\" |$4 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"Saw2BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw2.htm|title=Saw II (2005)|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=March 5, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Saw III]]''\n|{{start date|2006|10|27}}\n|$80,238,724\n|$84,635,551\n|$164,874,275\n|align=\"center\" |$10 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"Saw3BOM\"/>\n|-\n|''[[Saw IV]]''\n|{{start date|2007|10|26}}\n|$63,300,095\n|$76,052,538\n|$139,352,633\n|align=\"center\" |$10 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_12255.html|title=Darren Lynn Bousman Interview, SAW 4|last=Roberts|first=Sheila|publisher=MoviesOnline.ca|year=2007|access-date=March 5, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61rOpPayn|archive-date=September 21, 2011|url-status=live|quote=Bousman: The budget is exactly the same as it was for ''Saw 3''.}}</ref><ref name=\"Saw4BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw4.htm|title=Saw IV (2007)|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Saw V]]''\n|{{start date|2008|10|24}}\n|$56,746,769\n|$57,117,290\n|$113,864,059\n|align=\"center\" |$10.8 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"Saw5BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw5.htm|title=Saw V (2008)|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Saw VI]]''\n|{{start date|2009|10|23}}\n|$27,693,292\n|$40,540,337\n|$68,233,629\n|align=\"center\" |$11 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"Saw6BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw6.htm|title=Saw VI (2009)|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 10, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Saw 3D]]''\n|{{Start date|2010|10|29}}\n|$45,710,178\n|$90,440,256\n|$136,150,434\n|align=\"center\"|$20 million\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"budget\">{{cite news| url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19116 | title=Kevin Greutert Talks to BD from the Set of 'Saw VII 3D' | work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] | publisher= The Collective | last= Miska|first= Brad | date=February 15, 2010 | access-date=February 16, 2010 | quote=At this point I view it as getting paid to go through a $17 million dollar one-man 3D film school program, so how's that for looking at the bright side of a dark situation?| archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5namYxahq | archive-date=February 16, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n|{{start date|2017|10|27}}\n|$38,052,832\n|$64,900,056\n|$102,952,888\n|align=\"center\" |$10 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"JigsawBOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw2017.htm|title=Jigsaw (2017)|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=2 align=\"center\"|Total\n!$453,966,900\n!$522,305,866\n!$976,272,768\n!align=\"center\" |$77 million\n!\n|}\n\n===Critical and public response===\nOn [[IGN]]'s list of the top twenty-five film franchises of all time, the ''Saw'' series ranked as 25th.<ref>{{cite web|date=2006-11-20|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/746/746875p1.html|title=IGN: Top 25 Movie Franchises of All Time: #25|work=[[IGN]] |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061202074915/http://movies.ign.com/articles/746/746875p1.html |archive-date= 2006-12-02 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=99% border=\"1\"\n! align=\"center\" | '''Film'''\n! align=\"center\" | '''[[Rotten Tomatoes]]'''\n! align=\"center\" | '''[[Metacritic]]'''\n! align=\"center\" | '''[[CinemaScore]]'''\n|-\n|-\n| ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n| 49% (184 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw/|title=Saw|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| 46 (32 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw/critic-reviews|title=Saw (2004): Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| C+<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web | title = CinemaScore | url = https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ | website = [[CinemaScore]] }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Saw II]]''\n| 37% (122 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_ii/|title=Saw II|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| 40 (28 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-ii/critic-reviews|title=Saw II (2005): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B+<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw III]]''\n| 28% (92 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_3/|title=Saw III|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| 48 (16 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-iii/critic-reviews|title=Saw III (2006): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw IV]]''\n| 20% (81 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_4/|title=Saw IV|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=November 15, 2008}}</ref>\n| 36 (16 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-iv/critic-reviews|title=Saw IV (2007): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw V]]''\n| 13% (76 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_v/|title=Saw V|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| 20 (13 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-v/critic-reviews|title=Saw V (2008): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=November 15, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|C<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw VI]]''\n| 39% (72 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_VI/|title=Saw VI|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=July 11, 2010}}</ref>\n| 30 (12 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-vi/critic-reviews|title=Saw VI (2009): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=October 24, 2009}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n| 10% (79 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw3d/|title=Saw 3D|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=August 29, 2011}}</ref>\n| 24 (17 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-3d/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Saw 3D (2010)|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|B\u2013<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n| 33% (87 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jigsaw (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jigsaw_2017|website=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| 39 (18 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jigsaw Reviews|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/jigsaw|website=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|}\n\n==Other media==\n{{main|List of Saw media}}\n\n===Video games===\n[[Japan]]ese video game company [[Konami]] currently owns the rights to the ''Saw'' interactive video game property. Konami stated in mid-2009 that they wanted to make ''Saw'' a series of video games to supplement the films. They also wish to make ''Saw'' their next big survival horror franchise next to their other property, ''[[Silent Hill]]''. They stated that because ''Saw'' focuses on visual intensity and ''Silent Hill'' focuses on psychological terror, both could exist in the video game industry without directly competing against each other.<ref name= \"Will Saw Be Konami's Second Great Horror Franchise?\">{{cite news|url=http://weblogs.variety.com/the_cut_scene/2009/04/silent-hill-say-hello-to-your-new-brother-jigsawkonami-has-confirmed-an-earlier-cut-scene-report-that-it-has-bought-the-pub.html|title=Will Saw Be Konami's Second Great Horror Franchise?|work=The Cut Scene|date=2009-04-02|access-date=2009-08-04}}</ref>\n\nThe first game in the series, ''[[Saw (video game)|Saw]]'', set between the first and second film in the series, was initially released on October 6, 2009.<ref name=WanWhannell>{{Cite web|url=http://www.360-hq.com/article-2382-thread-1-0.html|title=Producer James Wan On Saw The Video Game &#124; 360-HQ.COM|website=www.360-hq.com|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Nick|last=Wingfield|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118092768266523504 |title=A Start Up's Risky Niche: Movie-Based Videogames|date=2007-06-04|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=2008-01-30|url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/848/848533p1.html|title=Saw announced|access-date=2008-01-30}}</ref> with a sequel ''[[Saw II: Flesh & Blood]]'', released on October 19, 2010, for the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3, ten days before the release of the seventh film, ''Saw 3D''.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/57520/Jigsaw_Returns.php|title=Jigsaw Returns!|publisher=[[Gamasutra]]|date=April 9, 2010|access-date=April 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[David Tapp]] and [[Amanda Young]] were released as part of the downloadable ''Saw Chapter'' for the video game ''[[Dead by Daylight]]''.<ref name= \"Dead by Daylight\">{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/gaming/2018/01/22/dead-by-daylight-saw-dlc-confirmed-jigsaw-coming-tomorrow/|publisher=Comic Book|title=Dead By Daylight Confirms Saw DLC, Releasing Tomorrow|date=2018-01-22|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref>\n\n===Comic books===\n''Saw: Rebirth'', a [[comic book]] prequel to the original film released to promote ''Saw II''. Its [[canon (fiction)|canonicity]] was later contradicted by events in ''Saw IV''. It is, however, the first canonical appearance of Jigsaw's wife, Jill, who was later introduced into the film series in ''Saw III'', and established still-canonical elements of Jigsaw's backstory (an engineer who is dying from brain cancer.)\n\n===Theme park attractions===\n* \"[[Saw: The Ride]]\" is a [[Gerstlauer Euro-Fighter]] roller coaster themed around the franchise, which opened on March 13, 2009, at [[Thorpe Park]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. It features an enclosed dark ride section with special effects, before cars travel outside and are pulled up a 100-foot vertical lift hill into a steep 100-degree drop.\n* [[Thorpe Park]] opened a temporary ''Saw'' attraction called \"Saw \u2014 Movie Bites\" for their 2009 Fright Nights event.\n* It was announced in October 2009 that Thorpe Park would also be adding a permanent, year-round [[live action]] horror [[maze]] themed around the ''Saw'' movies. It opened at the start of the 2010 season, and features six scenes representing one iconic trap from each movie to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hauntedattractions.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=570&Itemid=2|title=Thorpe: SAW Alive exclusive details|work=Haunted Attractions|publisher=hauntedattractions.co.uk|access-date=2009-11-29}}</ref>\n* \"[[Halloween Horror Nights|Saw: Game Over]]\" was a 2009 maze made by [[Universal Parks & Resorts|Universal Studios]] for [[Halloween Horror Nights]], based on characters, traps and scenes from the films.<ref name= \"Sneek Peak At Universal's Saw: Game Over Maze!\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11469|publisher=Shock Till You Drop|title=Sneek Peak At Universal's Saw: Game Over Maze!|date=2009-08-19|access-date=2009-11-12}}</ref> At the [[Universal Studios Hollywood]] rendition of Horror Nights it was titled ''Saw: Game Over'', while at the [[Universal Studios Florida]] rendition, it was simply titled ''Saw''.\n* \"Saw\", a themed haunted house, operated during the month of October at [http://www.frightdome.com Fright Dome], [[Circus Circus Las Vegas]]. It featured interactive, handcrafted replicas of the \"games\" set by [[Jigsaw Killer|Jigsaw]]. It was introduced in 2009 and partnered with [[Lionsgate]] and [[Twisted Pictures]].\n* In 2010, \"[[Halloween Fright Nights]]\" at [[Warner Bros. Movie World]] featured a maze created by [[Sudden Impact Entertainment]], featuring characters, traps and scenes from the films. The maze was simply titled \"Saw Maze\".\n* \"Saw Haunted Attraction\" was a maze at the Brea Plaza Shopping Center in 2008 created by Sinister Pointe Haunted Attractions.\n* \"SAWMANIA\" was a fan event in New York. Eventgoers were able to meet actors and directors, and view props used in the films.\n\n=== Fan films universe ===\n''Main article: [[Saw fan films universe]]''\n\nThe impact of the ''Saw'' films inspired creators from all over the world to create [[fan film]]s based on the franchise. The films are in no way affiliated with [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate films]] or [[Twisted Pictures]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n* [[Splatter film]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Saw (franchise)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n; Databases\n* [http://allmovie.com/work/saw-film-series-356901 ''Saw'' film series] at [[Allmovie]]\n* [http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=Saw.htm ''Saw'' film series] at [[Box Office Mojo]]\n; Official sites\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041126235053/http://www.sawmovie.com/ ''Saw'' website] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071002065430/http://www.saw2.com/ ''Saw II'' website] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061116073244/http://saw3.com/ ''Saw III website''] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071024161726/http://movies.break.com/saw4/ ''Saw IV'' website] (archive)\n* [http://www.saw5.com ''Saw V'' website]\n; Other links\n* [http://www.thorpepark.com/ Thorpe Park] - home to two ''Saw'' attractions\n* [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/scott-mendelson/goodbye-john-a-farewell-t_b_775552.html?view=print Goodbye John: A Farewell to Saw, as Jigsaw Lays His Last Trap] by Scott Mendelson\n\n{{Saw}}\n\n[[Category:Film franchises introduced in 2004]]\n[[Category:Horror film franchises]]\n[[Category:Splatter films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:American teen horror films]]\n[[Category:Saw (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate franchises]]\n[[Category:Films about mass murder]]\n[[Category:American splatter films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n", "name_user": "2405:6e00:1f08:301:710a:346d:c3ba:cefe", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFan films universe)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saw_(franchise)"}
{"title_page": "Blacktop (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Blacktop\n| image          = Blacktop.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[T. J. Scott]]\n| producer       =\n| writer         = Kevin Lund<br/>T. J. Scott\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Meat Loaf]]<br/>[[Kristin Davis]]<br/>[[Lochlyn Munro]]\n| music          = Ennio Di Berardo\n| cinematography = Attila Szalay\n| editing        = Bert Kish\n| distributor    = [[HBO]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2000|10|20}}\n| runtime        = 100 minutes\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $3,500,000 (estimated)\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Blacktop''''' is a 2000 Canadian [[television film|made-for-television]] [[thriller film]] directed by [[T. J. Scott]] and starring [[Meat Loaf]], [[Kristin Davis]], and [[Lochlyn Munro]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Orphan Black Wins Big at the Canadian Screen Awards|url = http://orphanblack.space.ca/orphan-black-wins-big-at-the-canadian-screen-awards/|website = Space.ca|accessdate = 2015-12-08|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151122172333/http://orphanblack.space.ca/orphan-black-wins-big-at-the-canadian-screen-awards/|archive-date = 2015-11-22|url-status = dead}}</ref> It aired on [[HBO]] on October 20, 2000.\n\n==Plot==\nWhen David ([[Lochlyn Munro]]), a comedian, gets a three night gig at a trucker's bar, his girlfriend, Sylvia ([[Kristin Davis]]), leaves him and accepts a ride from a trucker, Jack ([[Meat Loaf]]).\n\nProblems arise when we discover that Jack may be a deranged [[serial killer]] of young women.\nDavid is starting a chase with the trucker and his girlfriend which is not aware of the danger. Jack starts a game with David, in which Sylvia's life is at stake.\n\nTravelling together with Sylvia in his truck named \"Goliath\", Jack is leaving some clues to David as he follows them, at the same time acting as a \"good stranger\" to Sylvia, telling her stories about his life, and as we later learn difficult childhood in which he encountered bad treatment of his father towards his mother, (as Jack then recalls he killed his father in defense of mother).\n\nFollowing chase, David meets Jack and Sylvia in deserted place Jack opens fire from his [[rifle]], Sylvia momentarily learns about his real plans, and tries to escape (unsuccessfully).\n\nAfter several miles of further chase they're meeting again for a dramatic final scene, in which David is eventually able to defeat Jack, though this isn't possible without blood shed (Jack cut off Sylvia's finger \"to teach her discipline\").\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Meat Loaf]] (as Meat Loaf Aday) as Jack\n* [[Kristin Davis]] as Sylvia\n* [[Lochlyn Munro]] as David\n* [[Victoria Pratt]] as Charlie\n* Blu Mankuma as Buck\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0235235|title=Blacktop}}\n\n{{T. J. Scott}}\n\n[[Category:2000 films]]\n[[Category:2000s thriller films]]\n[[Category:Canadian television films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by T.J. Scott]]\n[[Category:HBO Films films]]\n[[Category:Trucker films]]\n\n\n{{2000s-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Blacktop\n| image          = Blacktop.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[T.J. Scott]]\n| producer       =\n| writer         = Kevin Lund<br/>T.J. Scott\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Meat Loaf]]<br/>[[Kristin Davis]]<br/>[[Lochlyn Munro]]\n| music          = Ennio Di Berardo\n| cinematography = Attila Szalay\n| editing        = Bert Kish\n| distributor    = [[HBO]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2000|10|20}}\n| runtime        = 100 minutes\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $3,500,000 (estimated)\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Blacktop''''' is a 2000 American [[thriller film]] directed by [[T.J. Scott]] and starring [[Meat Loaf]], [[Kristin Davis]], and [[Lochlyn Munro]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Orphan Black Wins Big at the Canadian Screen Awards|url = http://orphanblack.space.ca/orphan-black-wins-big-at-the-canadian-screen-awards/|website = Space.ca|accessdate = 2015-12-08|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151122172333/http://orphanblack.space.ca/orphan-black-wins-big-at-the-canadian-screen-awards/|archive-date = 2015-11-22|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nWhen David ([[Lochlyn Munro]]), a comedian, gets a three night gig at a trucker's bar, his girlfriend, Sylvia ([[Kristin Davis]]), leaves him and accepts a ride from a trucker, Jack ([[Meat Loaf]]).\n\nProblems arise when we discover that Jack may be a deranged [[serial killer]] of young women.\nDavid is starting a chase with the trucker and his girlfriend which is not aware of the danger. Jack starts a game with David, in which Sylvia's life is at stake.\n\nTravelling together with Sylvia in his truck named \"Goliath\", Jack is leaving some clues to David as he follows them, at the same time acting as a \"good stranger\" to Sylvia, telling her stories about his life, and as we later learn difficult childhood in which he encountered bad treatment of his father towards his mother, (as Jack then recalls he killed his father in defense of mother).\n\nFollowing chase, David meets Jack and Sylvia in deserted place Jack opens fire from his [[rifle]], Sylvia momentarily learns about his real plans, and tries to escape (unsuccessfully).\n\nAfter several miles of further chase they're meeting again for a dramatic final scene, in which David is eventually able to defeat Jack, though this isn't possible without blood shed (Jack cut off Sylvia's finger \"to teach her discipline\").\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Meat Loaf]] (as Meat Loaf Aday) as Jack\n* [[Kristin Davis]] as Sylvia\n* [[Lochlyn Munro]] as David\n* [[Victoria Pratt]] as Charlie\n* Blu Mankuma as Buck\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0235235|title=Blacktop}}\n\n[[Category:2000 films]]\n[[Category:2000s thriller films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Trucker films]]\n\n\n{{2000s-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DoubleCross", "label": "safe", "comment": "add template and categories", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blacktop_(film)"}
